Overview.Summary: The 2019 South Ossetian parliamentary election in the region of South Ossetia has been met with controversy and condemnation from Georgia, who claim it violates their sovereignty and territorial integrity (1). The election has also sparked talks of cooperation between South Ossetia and Crimea (3), and has been a topic of discussion in Iran (5). The ruling party, United Ossetia, lost their majority in the election (6). There have also been concerns about Russia's increasing influence and possible annexation of South Ossetia (8). Statistics on voter turnout will be published on May 24 (9). Language links for more information can be found at the top of the Wikipedia page (10).

Timeline.Text: The parliamentary elections in occupied South Ossetia are held and Georgia condemns them as a violation of its sovereignty and territorial integrity.
An agreement on cooperation between Crimea and South Ossetia is signed at the Yalta International Economic Forum.
The Wikipedia page for the 2019 South Ossetian parliamentary election is created and discussed on Talk page.
Election fever spreads to the breakaway territories, including South Ossetia, where 34 MPs will be elected.
Russia's annexation of South Ossetia continues as South Ossetian military personnel with Russian citizenship become members of the Russian military.
Statistics Finland publishes a review on voting turnover for the parliamentary elections, which will examine the voting turnout by various factors.
The ruling party loses its majority in South Ossetia's parliament.
The case for international recognition of South Ossetia is made, with the potential for increased economic, political, and cultural contacts with the outside world.
The Wikipedia page for the 2019 South Ossetian parliamentary election is updated to include language links.

The ruling United Ossetia Party, led by incumbent President Anatoly Bibilov, lost their majority in parliament, winning only 14 seats (17). The elections were condemned by the Georgian government as a violation of their sovereignty and territorial integrity (1). The Group of Friends of Georgia, which includes countries such as the United States and United Kingdom, also released a joint statement expressing their concern over the elections (10). The results of the elections were not recognized by the international community, with some calling the elections "laughably illegitimate" (18). The election also sparked discussions on the potential for international recognition of South Ossetia (19).

The ruling party loses its majority in the South Ossetian parliament.
The Group of Friends of Georgia issues a joint statement condemning the election.
Statistics Finland publishes a review on voting turnout, which includes information on the South Ossetian election.
Election fever takes over the breakaway territories of Georgia.
The BJP wins a sweeping victory in the Indian Lok Sabha election.
Germany, the most populous nation in the EU, sends 96 Members of the European Parliament to represent them.
Hungary's Prime Minister Viktor Orban addresses supporters after the preliminary results of the European Parliament election are announced.
Greeks vote in an early national election, with all 300 seats in the Hellenic Parliament up for contest.
